Both the FBX and GLB files just open as a black sphere in a couple of different free software. Am I missing something? Is it supposed to look like that? Any help would be much appreciated, thanks!

there are three ways to view a 3D work like Peter's: 1) on the feral file site 2) through the downloadable applications for windows, mac, and linux 3) open the model and view it directly. i haven't looked at the FBX model directly, but i think the experience is probably inside of the sphere. @peter burr can you offer some advice?

Greetings @mwilmink - Thanks for supporting this work! I'm excited you picked up COUNT ZERO FOUR. I am in accord with the feedback @Casey REAS offers here. Additionally, the download includes everything you need to host this file in a custom 3D-viewer on a web page (simply host it the way you host a traditional web 1.0 / 2.0  page on a server). The 'black sphere' you see when you open the fbx in Blender is intentional. I think of that version of COUNT ZERO FOUR as a seed or a nut you must crack open (aligning with the botanical themes of this exhibit). If you would like to simulate the view you see in the feral file online exhibition using personal software such as Cinema4D, I recommend enabling 'backface culling'. Many video game engines do this automatically, as does the custom 3D viewer I included in the html download (which is what you are seeing in the actual exhibition).  This work is designed to open up like an X-ray when the 3-D viewer is sensitive to the direction of the sculpture's 'normals'.

Hi @Casey REAS and @peter burr thanks so much to you both for your notes. I suspected it was something like that, but I didn't have enough tech knowledge of 3D software to be sure, haha. Peter, it's a great work, we're very happy to have it as our first "digital collection"!

@nancybakercahill ’s mutant artwork “Stipstream 001” takes inspiration from the literary genre known as slipstream fiction, which deals with “the familiar strange or the strange familiar.” The digital sculpture is based on an IRL sculpture made of torn graphite drawings that were recombined and translated into a 3D object that resembles a simulated botanical form. To add on to @Casey REAS — one thing I’ve been thinking a lot about these last few months is (for lack of a better phrase) a "collaborative custody" model.

The status quo for holding digital assets (art, coins, etc...) is one of two options: A) Give control of your artwork to a 3rd-party . Or B) take full responsibility into your own hands with a crypto wallet (eg: MetaMask, Autonomy).
I think there's a model where a platform like Feral File could help (collaborate) with custody in a way that doesn't centralize asset control.

Two years ago we built a partitioned wallet architecture for Bitcoin that combined a mobile app with your own private full node in the cloud. This gives independence and the ability to safely set emergency contacts and beneficiaries to make sure your wealth is always protected.
It was possible for Bitcoin because multisig is built into the Bitcoin protocol. (Unfortunately Ethereum and Tezos don't have this built in...)
We've been researching ways to do this using something known as "Verifiable secret sharing", or VSS.
I'm convinced it's possible for NFTs.
The benefit to this model is that individuals and companies could help you hold your assets without the ability to gain access to your assets. It's a collaborative custody model.
To come fully circle, @Raimans our goal is  help provide independence and resilience, regardless of what chain your Feral File NFTs are on.
If there are certain benefits offered to specific chains now, that is only a short term thing. We aim to be as open and interoperable as possible, across all the chains we support.

@TheGramCollection 📟🍀🌻🪆 I would divide wallets into three types:
1. software app
2. web browser extensions / apps
3. hardware (dedicated device)
Hardware wallets are the most secure because the attack surface that someone can get the keys out is (hopefully) well tested and hardened.

Software apps (like Autonomy or MetaMask) use the secure storage on mobile phones to better isolate the keys. I trust Apple to get the security of their keystore right. Android is more tricky... because the security really depends on the vendor (eg: HTC) not Google. It's also worth noting that when the app is running and doing things those keys are extracted into software so the security would then depend on how well isolated the app environment is.
Anything web browser I would never trust. Literally the security model of the browser is that the server is trusted -- not the client.
Hope that helps.
